Explanation:

I inspected the provided controller code for the GET /api/users/:id route (function getUserById). The controller's comments and implementation indicate:

- @desc: "Get user by ID" — this maps to the operation summary/description.
- @route: "GET /api/users/:id" — the endpoint includes a path parameter "id".
- @access: "Private/Admin" — the endpoint requires authentication/authorization (this is noted in the description; the controller itself only returns normal responses and throws a 404 when not found).
- Behavior and responses from the controller:
  - On success it returns the user document with the password field explicitly excluded (.select('-password')). From surrounding code and other responses, the user object contains at least: _id, name, email, isAdmin.
  - If the user is not found the controller sets status 404 and throws "User not found" — so the operation should include a 404 response with an error message body.

I therefore produced an OpenAPI 3.1 Operation Object for GET /api/users/{id} that includes:
- summary and description derived from the controller comment and access level.
- a required path parameter "id" of type string.
- responses:
  - 200: application/json with a schema for the returned user object (properties: _id, name, email, isAdmin).
  - 404: application/json with a schema containing a "message" string (the controller throws an error message).

No other fields (e.g., security objects, additional response codes) were added beyond what is supported by the controller implementation and comments.

